1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,960
Okay, so

2
00:00:01,960 --> 00:00:06,780
we are starting an
overview of Greek history.

3
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:09,080
Remember the story so far.

4
00:00:09,360 --> 00:00:12,740
We talked about the Bronze Age and

5
00:00:12,740 --> 00:00:17,140
where Mycenaean Greece was trading

6
00:00:17,140 --> 00:00:19,420
and fighting with the rest of the world.

7
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:22,400
And then the Bronze Age
collapse happened and

8
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:24,680
Mycenaean Greece came to an end.

9
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:26,660
And because of its destruction,

10
00:00:27,020 --> 00:00:31,280
this allowed for massive
innovation throughout Greece.

11
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:34,480
So we saw the introduction of
the polis, the city -state.

12
00:00:35,780 --> 00:00:40,700
We saw the beginning of
the use of the alphabet.

13
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:46,280
And so literacy rates increased
radically throughout Greece.

14
00:00:46,580 --> 00:00:50,220
And we saw Homer who gave us the Iliad

15
00:00:50,220 --> 00:00:52,020
and the Odyssey.

16
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,520
So today,

17
00:00:54,680 --> 00:01:00,620
I'm just going to go over the
overview of Greek history,

18
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:02,720
mainly focusing on the polis.

19
00:01:03,220 --> 00:01:07,620
So one thing to understand
about the polis is

20
00:01:07,620 --> 00:01:11,320
that geography is destiny.

21
00:01:13,580 --> 00:01:16,500
Geography is destiny.

22
00:01:16,700 --> 00:01:19,420
And this basically means that

23
00:01:19,420 --> 00:01:24,400
your geography will determine the culture,

24
00:01:24,680 --> 00:01:26,700
the economy, and

25
00:01:26,700 --> 00:01:29,700
the political structure of your society.

26
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,760
And we see that with the Greek polis.

27
00:01:33,020 --> 00:01:35,320
The Greek geography is very diverse.

28
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:38,080
There are mountains, there are rivers,

29
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:41,340
there are plains, and
there are coastlines.

30
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:44,500
And depending on where

31
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:46,360
you are geographically in Greece,

32
00:01:46,580 --> 00:01:49,860
you will have a different type of polis.

33
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:54,040
And so the two classic
examples are Sparta and Athens.

34
00:01:54,680 --> 00:02:00,460
Sparta and Athens are the two most
dominant polis in about the year 500 BC.

35
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:04,380
So let's first talk about Sparta.

36
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:09,920
So Sparta is located on the Pelonese.

37
00:02:10,540 --> 00:02:11,840
This is Sparta.

38
00:02:12,620 --> 00:02:18,340
And the land around Sparta
is basically plains,

39
00:02:18,600 --> 00:02:21,200
which makes it ideal for agriculture.

40
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:24,740
Okay? So for most of its history,

41
00:02:25,020 --> 00:02:29,180
Sparta was an agricultural nation.

42
00:02:30,300 --> 00:02:31,660
And because

43
00:02:31,660 --> 00:02:35,780
it is ideal for agriculture,

44
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:38,700
it needs people to work the land.

45
00:02:39,100 --> 00:02:41,520
And through its conquest,

46
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,900
Sparta developed a slave system.

47
00:02:45,220 --> 00:02:47,300
Okay? And these people are called helots.

48
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:51,080
And helots are just slaves in Sparta

49
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:52,860
that work the land. They are farmers.

50
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:56,640
And these are people who have
been conquered by Sparta.

51
00:02:57,660 --> 00:03:01,760
And because there are so many helots,
okay, the ratio is about 10 to 1.

52
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,380
So for every one helot, sorry, for
every one Spartan, there's 10 helots.

53
00:03:06,980 --> 00:03:11,980
Sparta had to become a military
society in order to control the helots.

54
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:16,860
So it created an education system in

55
00:03:16,860 --> 00:03:20,360
order to train its
citizens to be soldiers.

56
00:03:20,360 --> 00:03:22,800
So the system worked like this.

57
00:03:23,460 --> 00:03:27,000
About age 7, you left your family

58
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,340
and you were put into
a boarding school where

59
00:03:30,340 --> 00:03:34,240
you were watched over by kids
who were older than you.

60
00:03:34,380 --> 00:03:35,740
Okay? Maybe 11 or 12.

61
00:03:36,340 --> 00:03:39,460
And obviously, you put
young kids with older kids,

62
00:03:39,640 --> 00:03:43,420
the older kids will beat the
crap out of these young kids

63
00:03:43,420 --> 00:03:45,600
who are about 7 or 8. And

64
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:50,340
this instills the idea of emotional
discipline into the system.

65
00:03:50,340 --> 00:03:54,720
And this is what happened to the children.
Now, when these children became teenagers,

66
00:03:55,200 --> 00:03:58,960
they were paired with a mentor

67
00:03:58,960 --> 00:04:02,640
who was maybe 25 to about 30, okay?

68
00:04:02,740 --> 00:04:05,640
An older adult. And they became lovers.

69
00:04:07,640 --> 00:04:11,100
The Spartans did not
consider this homosexuality.

70
00:04:11,160 --> 00:04:12,560
We would consider it homosexuality.

71
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:15,440
But they themselves did not
consider this homosexuality.

72
00:04:15,520 --> 00:04:17,720
Okay? They just considered this as a

73
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:21,780
way to build emotional cohesion,

74
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:25,380
love among its soldiers.

75
00:04:26,660 --> 00:04:28,640
And about age 18 or 19,

76
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:31,780
the students would graduate and

77
00:04:31,780 --> 00:04:36,100
they would go on to marry
and have their own families.

78
00:04:36,680 --> 00:04:41,260
But the Spartan soldiers were
all required to eat together.

79
00:04:41,640 --> 00:04:45,660
Okay? So the soldiers, even though they had
families, they were still required to eat together.

80
00:04:45,680 --> 00:04:47,640
They were required to train
together and to eat together.

81
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:52,480
Spartans had no private property.

82
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:56,920
Everything, including the
helots, belonged to everyone.

83
00:04:57,240 --> 00:05:00,180
Okay? So it's basically like
communism or proto -communism.

84
00:05:00,380 --> 00:05:01,940
They had no money system.

85
00:05:02,140 --> 00:05:06,480
They had no wealth. Everything
belonged to everyone.

86
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:10,020
And it was a brutal state.

87
00:05:10,220 --> 00:05:14,480
The Spartans were notorious
for being brutal people.

88
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,360
So an example is the helots.

89
00:05:17,580 --> 00:05:22,980
So they had a campaign of terror to
maintain control over the helots.

90
00:05:23,300 --> 00:05:27,180
So young soldiers would often be

91
