order to find new markets,

167
00:09:49,340 --> 00:09:51,060
in order to bring goods and

168
00:09:51,060 --> 00:09:54,440
ideas back to Athens.

169
00:09:55,020 --> 00:09:58,480
Okay? Because

170
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:00,760
Athens was expansionist,

171
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,020
its cultural system,

172
00:10:03,320 --> 00:10:05,820
its cultural beliefs was very different.

173
00:10:05,820 --> 00:10:07,880
From the Spartans.

174
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,200
Okay? So whereas the Spartans
were very conservative,

175
00:10:10,520 --> 00:10:14,140
the Athenians had a policy,

176
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:16,720
had a belief in the idea of eudaimonia.

177
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:19,860
Eudaimonia. So

178
00:10:19,860 --> 00:10:22,980
eudaimonia is a Greek word

179
00:10:22,980 --> 00:10:25,960
and it means human flourishing.

180
00:10:26,940 --> 00:10:29,040
Flourishing. And

181
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:33,400
the idea here is to be
the best that you can be.

182
00:10:33,560 --> 00:10:36,480
All right? So the example of eudaimonia,

183
00:10:36,660 --> 00:10:38,680
the most famous example
of eudaimonia is this.

184
00:10:39,060 --> 00:10:42,800
In Homer's Iliad, the main
character is Achilles.

185
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:48,780
And Achilles is the best warrior
of the Greeks against Troy.

186
00:10:49,900 --> 00:10:53,120
And Achilles says this in the book.

187
00:10:53,180 --> 00:10:56,780
He says, before I came
to Troy, I saw a prophet.

188
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:59,880
I saw a fortune teller
and he told me my fortune.

189
00:11:00,420 --> 00:11:04,060
He said I could choose
to not come to Troy.

190
00:11:04,620 --> 00:11:08,340
And live to be a, live a very long,

191
00:11:08,560 --> 00:11:09,900
healthy life.

192
00:11:10,320 --> 00:11:11,700
But I'd be a nobody.

193
00:11:12,640 --> 00:11:17,080
If I came to Troy, I would die
young, but I would die as a hero.

194
00:11:17,540 --> 00:11:20,620
I would be remembered by everyone.

195
00:11:22,060 --> 00:11:26,280
Everyone would sing of
my glory and my triumph.

196
00:11:27,020 --> 00:11:31,480
So that was my choice. I could live for
a very long time and just be a nobody.

197
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:35,140
Or I could be a hero and die young.

198
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:38,260
And he said, well for
me, that's not a choice.

199
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:41,040
Okay? For me,

200
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:44,320
to be alive means to achieve eudaimonia.

201
00:11:44,560 --> 00:11:46,460
I have to be the best that I can be.

202
00:11:46,660 --> 00:11:50,960
And therefore, my only
option is to come to Troy

203
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:52,220
and die a hero.

204
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:54,920
Okay? And that's the mentality in Athens.

205
00:11:55,180 --> 00:11:58,620
It is much better to die young as a hero

206
00:11:58,620 --> 00:12:01,400
than to live a long time as a nobody.

207
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:04,760
Whereas in Spartans, we're
the complete opposite.

208
00:12:04,980 --> 00:12:08,880
Okay? It's just better to be a nobody and

209
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:13,920
get along with everyone
than it is to die as a hero.

210
00:12:14,080 --> 00:12:16,820
Okay? So very opposite societies.

211
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,000
But, and what this did,
this idea of eudaimonia,

212
00:12:22,120 --> 00:12:27,100
it made Athens into a
very competitive society.

213
00:12:27,480 --> 00:12:30,500
Okay? Because if everyone's
trying to achieve eudaimonia,

214
00:12:32,880 --> 00:12:34,520
then you're going to have
a lot of competition.

215
00:12:34,860 --> 00:12:37,820
Okay? Because they're
going to be one hero.

216
00:12:38,340 --> 00:12:39,580
Everyone cannot be a hero.

217
00:12:39,700 --> 00:12:40,940
They're going to be one hero.

218
00:12:41,180 --> 00:12:45,900
So again, the example is Homer's Iliad.

219
00:12:46,500 --> 00:12:50,460
And when Achilles got into
a fight with Agamemnon,

220
00:12:52,580 --> 00:12:54,260
Achilles basically says, I don't like you.

221
00:12:54,280 --> 00:12:55,680
You're a dog. I'm not
going to fight for you.

222
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:57,500
And Agamemnon says, I don't need you.

223
00:12:57,820 --> 00:13:00,680
What Achilles did was,
he went to his mother,

224
00:13:00,860 --> 00:13:02,980
who was a goddess, and

225
00:13:02,980 --> 00:13:06,660
Achilles said to Thetis, his mother,

226
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,840
could you please get the
gods to help the Trojans

227
00:13:13,740 --> 00:13:15,020
so that

228
00:13:15,020 --> 00:13:19,700
Agamemnon would have to come beg
for my help against the Trojans.

229
00:13:19,880 --> 00:13:21,860
Okay? He was basically committing treason.

230
00:13:22,340 --> 00:13:25,160
And in the Greek world,
you're allowed to do that

231
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:28,600
because the most important
thing is eudaimonia.

232
00:13:28,600 --> 00:13:30,660
To achieve eudaimonia.

233
00:13:30,880 --> 00:13:34,120
Okay? Does that make sense?
It's a very weird world, but

234
00:13:34,120 --> 00:13:36,680
in Athens, it's extremely
competitive where

235
00:13:36,680 --> 00:13:41,660
everyone's trying to backstab each
other in order to become the hero.

236
00:13:42,300 --> 00:13:45,720
And because of this, because
there's so much competition,

237
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:51,320
Athens created a new
system called ostracize.

238
00:13:51,760 --> 00:13:54,700
Okay? So the idea here is, because

239
00:13:54,700 --> 00:13:57,380
the Athenians were so
at each other's throat,

240
00:13:58,960 --> 00:14:01,460
if someone was breaking the rules,

241
00:14:01,820 --> 00:14:04,980
or if someone was being too competitive
in the pursuit of eudaimonia,

242
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:09,160
the Athenian people could
choose to ostracize this person.

243
00:14:09,460 --> 00:14:12,740
And what this meant
was, you'd be banished,

244
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:15,880
okay, banished or exiled

245
00:14:18,200 --> 00:14:20,380
from Athens for ten years.

246
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:24,180
And this was considered
even worse than death.

247
00:14:24,300 --> 00:14:26,120
Okay, this punishment
was worse than death.

248
00:14:26,120 --> 00:14:29,180
The reason why is, in the Polish system,

249
00:14:29,720 --> 00:14:31,640
the only people that
mattered were citizens.

250
00:14:32,240 --> 00:14:33,480
Okay? And

251
00:14:33,480 --> 00:14:37,220
